Task 1.Intro: Show Your Data Wrangling Work.

- This rmd document will present information about TOD in Chicago, the capital city of Illinois, based on 2009 and 2017 ACS 5-year estimates data. and illustrate the following issues:

- Do households value transit-rich neighborhoods compared to others?

Task 2.Four Small-Multiple Visualizations Comparing Four Selected Census Variables Across Time and Space (TOD vs.non-TOD).

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data=st_union(tracts2009)) +
  geom_sf(data = allTracts.group, aes(fill = q6(TotalPop))) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = palette4,
                    labels = qBr2(allTracts.group, "TotalPop"),
                    name = "Total Population\n(Quintile Breaks)") +
  labs(title = "Total Population 2009-2017", subtitle = "Chicago; IL") +
  facet_wrap(c(~year,~TOD), ncol=4)+
  mapTheme() + theme(plot.title = element_text(size=24,face="bold"),legend.key.height = unit(35, "pt"),
   legend.key.width = unit(35, "pt"),legend.title = element_text(size = 15),legend.text = element_text(size = 15),plot.subtitle = element_text(size=18))

Mapping 1.Total Population.

From the set of graphs above, we can see that as time increases,

1. the population in the TOD area, especially in the central area, increases.

2. The population in Non-TOD area, there is a rise in the population in tracts close to the TOD area (e.g.along the southeast part of the river); there is a decrease in the population in tracts far from the TOD area (e.g.northwest & southwest parts).

Task 3.One Grouped Bar Plot Making These Same Comparisons.

allTracts.Summary %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -year, -TOD) %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, Value, fill = TOD)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free", ncol=5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#FFC300", "#C70039")) +
  labs(title = "Indicator differences across time and space") +
  plotTheme() + theme(legend.position="bottom")

kable(allTracts.Summary) %>%

2017 Non-TOD 4168.119 972.9492 61989.03 0.1650124
2017 TOD 3129.911 1027.6388 60847.14 0.2225269

As we can see from the image and table from Task3&4, the population within the TOD area does show a growing trend and the poverty rate has decreased. But with the overall economic growth from 2009 to 2017, it only shows that there is a preference for TOD areas at this point, but the economic benefits they bring are not significant.

Task 5.Two Graduated Symbol Maps Of Population and Rent

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = st_union(allTracts),fill = "#f0f9e8") +
  geom_sf(data = buffer,fill = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = tracts2009) +
  geom_sf(
          data=st_centroid(selectCentroids),
          pch=21,
          aes(size=TotalPop),
          fill="#FF5733",
          color="transparent",
          alpha=0.5,
          show="point"
          )+
  labs(title = "Population within 0.5 Mile of Each Railway Station")+
  mapTheme()+theme(plot.title = element_text(size=18))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = st_union(allTracts),fill = "#f0f9e8") +
  geom_sf(data = buffer,fill = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = tracts2009) +
  geom_sf(
          data=st_centroid(selectCentroids),
          pch=21,
          aes(size=MedRent),
          fill="#FF5733",
          color="transparent",
          alpha=0.5,
          show="point"
          )+
  labs(title = "Medium Rent within 0.5 Mile of Each Railway Station")+
  mapTheme()+theme(plot.title = element_text(size=18))

As we can see from the image above, The downtown area in the eastern part of Chicago, near the lake, enjoys higher population density and area rents, seemingly demonstrating a positive correlation between population and transportation development.

Task 6.Mean Rent as a Function of Distance to Rail stations

allTracts.PRICE <- rbind(tracts2009.rings.summary,tracts2017.rings.summary)


ggplot(allTracts.PRICE, 
       aes(distance, Mean_Rent, colour=year)) +
      geom_point(size=3) + 
  geom_line(size=2)

As we can see from the image above, However, in the distance-rent graph of Task6, we can see that the rent shows a trend of increasing and then decreasing with the distance of how home. Considering the actual TOD coverage until about 10 miles, the distance of TOD and the rent seem to show a negative correlation.

Summary

Through the above analysis, we can get the following conclusions

1.TOD areas are to some extent more attractive to the population than non-Non-TOD areas.

2.TOD areas do not generally represent higher rents and housing prices than non-Non-TOD areas, and may even present the opposite situation in some tracts.

Overall, it is not possible to make a strong case that households value transit-rich neighborhoods compared to others.
